For the typescript client, there's no channels, so I ended up making a custom "streaming parameter" object.

This object has no async magic, no loops. It's just when you call "stream.write(5)" it generates and sends a stream item right there in the write method. The bad part is that you can only call this after making the invocation, whereas with a channel you can load items and then call afterwards.

```
// channel style
var channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<Foo>();
foreach (foo in foos) {
  channel.Write(foo);
}
var result = await connection.invokeAsync("collectFoos", channel);
```

```
// flat placeholder style
var stream = connection.NewUploadStream();
var promise = connection.invoke("collectFoos", stream);
foreach (foo in foos) {
    await stream.write(foo);
}
var result = await promise;
```

The channel style one is definitely more elegant / more slick. The flat placeholder one better describes the underlying process; or the order in which things happen is more transparent.

What I want to do is just implement something similar in C#. Probably beef up the StreamPlaceholder class substantially, and have users call `stream.write(item)` like in typescript. This lets people do stuff like:

```
foreach (byte[] chunk in myFile) {
    await stream.write(chunk);
}
```

So basically this would allow for every iterable to be supported.

The downside is that there's something fun or magical about sending a channel "through to the server", and the nicer async staging results in cleaner code.

Thoughts?

