We would like this, too. Our company is currently in the process of replacing .NET Remoting with SignalR and it would simplify a lot, if server-side Requests including EF-Database queries could be cancelled from the Client with a CancellationToken.

We have seen following issues with the current state:

- We could use the Streaming API for Cancellation, so basically return IAsyncEnumerable<T> everywhere. But this is not idiomatic. It may make sense for cases, where the server returns many results which the client needs to iterate. But oftentimes the client just needs a single value or needs to wait for a process to finish. Returning IAsyncEnumerable<T> for those things is very confusing.

- Currently, clients can basically DOS-Attack our Server, by starting many heavy requests on the server without waiting for its results.

We also want to share a very rare, but hard-to-debug issue we encountered:

A long time ago we used following code with our HubConnectionBuilder:
```csharp
                    .AddNewtonsoftJsonProtocol(options =>
                    {
                        // ACHTUNG! Gleiche Serialisierungseinstellungen auch auf dem Server setzen.
                        options.PayloadSerializerSettings.TypeNameHandling = TypeNameHandling.Objects;
                    });
```
The reason was, that System.Text.Json was not able to handle class polymorphism before (it does now, so TypeNameHandling.Objects is not necessary anymore). Our SignalR hub expected a CancellationToken and our Client client passed one in. But what really happened was, that Newtonsoft.Json serialized the CancellationToken to the server which deserialized it. This worked until Garbage Collection, where an SEHException was thrown because the internal handle was invalid.

We may very well be the only ones, who had this problem. But it hints at the fact, that the current API is very confusing in this regard. You may believe, that the Server will cancel the request, but it actually doesn't.

