I've been going throught the source code the last few days and have a basic idea of how I'd implement it.
It would be largely based on the current `IHubFilter.InvokeMethodAsync` implementation:
```csharp
public interface IClientFilter {
    ValueTask OnSendAsync(ClientInvocationContext context,  Func<ClientInvocationContext, ValueTask> next);
}

public class ClientInvocationContext {
    public HubClientContext Context { get; } // this would have exactly the same public members as `HubCallerContext` but with a less confusing name given the server is the actual caller here
    public Hub Hub { get; } // I think this would be a single instance per "proxy" call. For instance, `Clients.All` would share the same instance for all clients targeted for the message.
    // the rest would be pretty much the same as a `HubInvocationContext` with a few name changes
    public string MethodName { get; }
    public IReadOnlyList<object?> MethodArguments { get; }
    public IServiceProvider ServiceProvider { get; }
}
```

The part in the code where things diverge a little is inside `HubConnectionHandler`. Here the filters would be sent to `HubConnectionContext` during `HubConnectionHandler.OnConnectedAsync` using the `HubConnectionContextOptions`.

On the constructor, we build the middleware invokation (much like the `DefaultHubDispatcher` does for `IHibFilters`) and "intercept" calls to both `HubConnectionContext.WriteAsync` methods.

To preserve performance when no filters are declared, we "short circuit" the call (again like the dispatcher does) and keep things running as usual.

When either method is called we'd have to check:
* if a middleware exists; and
* if the message is a `HubMethodInvocationMessages`.

If both are true, we'd create a `ClientInvocationContext` using either a `HubMessage` or `SerializedHubMessage` (using different internal constructors to preserve cache functionality) and call the middleware.

The hub instance may be a complication here because the connection instance lives way longer then the hub instances and it is not practical to keep one for each connection/handler.
To solve this, I think we could pass the hub instance with the `WriteAsync` call, but that may break compatibility.

In this case, the class would look like this:
```csharp
public class ClientInvocationContext {
    public HubClientContext Context { get; }
    public string HubName { get; }
    public string MethodName { get; }
    public IReadOnlyList<object?> MethodArguments { get; }
    public IServiceProvider ServiceProvider { get; }
}
```

We have no plans to add support for scanning for hubs via an attribute within an assembly. It should be possible to build something like this using reflection. 

```C#
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.SignalR;
using System.Reflection;

public static class MapAllHubsExtensions
{
    public static IEndpointConventionBuilder MapHubs(this IEndpointRouteBuilder routes)
    {
        var mapHub = typeof(HubEndpointRouteBuilderExtensions).GetMethod(nameof(HubEndpointRouteBuilderExtensions.MapHub), new[] { typeof(IEndpointRouteBuilder), typeof(string) })
            ?? throw new Exception("Could not find MapHub method");

        var group = routes.MapGroup("");

        foreach (var t in typeof(Program).Assembly.GetTypes())
        {
            if (typeof(Hub).IsAssignableFrom(t) && 
                t.IsPublic &&
                t.GetCustomAttribute<RouteAttribute>() is { } attribute)
            {
                mapHub.MakeGenericMethod(t).Invoke(null, new object[] { group, attribute.Template });
            }
        }

        return group;
    }
}
```

That would enable something like this:

```C#
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.SignalR;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

builder.Services.AddSignalR();

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapHubs();

app.Run();

[Route("/chat")]
public class ChatHub : Hub
{

}
```

Assembly scanning at runtime by default will break future plans to do ahead of time compilation, we don't want this to be a part of any experience in ASP.NET Core outside of MVC (which has this unfortunate default behavior). We can revisit this once we are able to replace runtime discovery with compile time source generation.

